You could use [Awaitility][1] instead of blocking for a fixed time.  
You could add methods for waiting for an event to your consumer:
```java
public Map&lt;String, String&gt; awaitEventMatching(final Predicate&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt; eventCondition) {
    return awaitEventMatching(eventCondition, Durations.TEN_SECONDS);
}

public Map&lt;String, String&gt; awaitEventMatching(final Predicate&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt; eventCondition,
                                              final Duration timeout) {
    return await(String.format(&quot;%s on topic %s&quot;, eventName, topic))
            .atMost(timeout)
            .pollInterval(500, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS)
            .until(() -&gt; events.stream().filter(eventCondition).findFirst(), Optional::isPresent)
            .orElseThrow();
}

public void awaitEventsMatching(final Predicate&lt;List&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt;&gt; eventsCondition) {
    awaitEventsMatching(eventsCondition, Durations.TEN_SECONDS);
}

public void awaitEventsMatching(final Predicate&lt;List&lt;Map&lt;String, String&gt;&gt;&gt; eventsCondition,
                                final Duration timeout) {
    await(String.format(&quot;%s on topic %s&quot;, eventName, topic))
            .atMost(timeout)
            .pollInterval(500, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS)
            .until(() -&gt; eventsCondition.test(events));
}
```

By this means you could wait for a single event matching a given criteria (`awaitEventMatching`) or check multiple events (`awaitEventsMatching`).  
Note that the `awaitEventMatching` returns the matched event for further assertions.

More on Awaitility on [Baeldung][2].


  [1]: http://www.awaitility.org/
  [2]: https://www.baeldung.com/awaitility-testing

